NODE_10_length_81978_cov_2030.005348	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	73940	75853	.	-	0	ID=MGA_1019;product=threonine/serine exporter family protein;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator,similar to AA sequence:RefSeq:WP_011068576.1;;locus_tag=LOCUS_10130;note=WP_011068576.1 threonine/serine exporter family protein (Bifidobacterium longum) [pid:93.2%25%2C q_cov:100.0%25%2C s_cov:100.0%25%2C Eval:0.0e+00],COG:COG2966:YjjP Uncharacterized membrane protein YjjP%2C DUF1212 family [Category:S%2C Aligned:307-463%2C Eval:3.0e-18%2C score:81.9%2C N-term missing],Domain:cl01118:ThrE Putative threonine/serine exporter. ThrE_2 is a family of membrane proteins involved in the export of threonine and serine. L-threonine%2C L-serine are both substrates for the exporter. The exporter exhibits nine-ten predicted transmembrane-spanning helices with long charged C and N termini and an amphipathic helix present within the N terminus. L-Threonine can be made by the amino acid-producing bacterium Corynebacterium glutamicum%2C but the potential for amino acid formation can be considerably improved by reducing its intracellular degradation into glycine and increasing its export by this exporter. Members of the family are found in Bacteria%2C Archaea%2C and the fungal kingdoms%2C and the family can exist either as a single long polypeptide chain or as two short polypeptides. All family members show an extended hydrophilic N-terminal domain with weak sequence similarity to portions of hydrolases (proteases%2C peptidases%2C and glycosidases)%3B this suggests that since this region is cytoplasmic to the membrane it may be generating the transport substrate%2C so may imply that threonine may not be the primary substrate and the ThrE has a subsidiary function. [Superfamily%2C Aligned:489-629%2C Eval:3.7e-17%2C score:76.2],MGA_1019
