NODE_37_length_12398_cov_1474.204448	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	5943	6500	.	+	0	ID=MGA_1762;product=histidine phosphatase family protein;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator,similar to AA sequence:RefSeq:WP_011068133.1;translation=MGIKLSKVAKAAKKYDHILIIMRHAKAEPFGDKGDSERELTDKGLKQAKAVGKGIESLGLVPDQISCSSVTRTRQTLDRMLKTFGDKPIVDYRISLYDGGVQAVFDELAHVKAKNRVFMIVGHEPTVSISAQWLASADSDGERLDLLNLGLSPASIVIMGSNKPFNEWQVHSGELLAVINVKDFD;locus_tag=LOCUS_17400;note=WP_011068133.1 histidine phosphatase family protein (Bifidobacterium) [pid:90.8%25%2C q_cov:100.0%25%2C s_cov:100.0%25%2C Eval:1.3e-92],Domain:cl11399:HP Histidine phosphatase domain found in a functionally diverse set of proteins%2C mostly phosphatases%3B contains a His residue which is phosphorylated during the reaction. The histidine phosphatase superfamily is so named because catalysis centers on a conserved His residue that is transiently phosphorylated during the catalytic cycle. Other conserved residues contribute to a 'phosphate pocket' and interact with the phospho group of substrate before%2C during and after its transfer to the His residue. Structure and sequence analyses show that different families contribute different additional residues to the 'phosphate pocket' and%2C more surprisingly%2C differ in the position%2C in sequence and in three dimensions%2C of a catalytically essential acidic residue. The superfamily may be divided into two main branches.The smaller branch 2 contains predominantly eukaryotic proteins. The catalytic functions in members include phytase%2C glucose-1-phosphatase and multiple inositol polyphosphate phosphatase. The in vivo roles of the mammalian acid phosphatases in branch 2 are not fully understood%2C although activity against lysophosphatidic acid and tyrosine-phosphorylated proteins has been demonstrated. [Superfamily%2C Aligned:19-157%2C Eval:1.4e-28%2C score:101.6],MGA_1762
